Ask HN: Insurance Agent Fraud?
text:
My insurance agent recently made a mistake while fulfilling a request from a lender. In short, she added coverage to my home/farm policy for a piece of equipment that I already had on my auto policy, thinking it was a new identical piece of equipment. This effectively revealed that I have been paying five or six times more than was necessary to have the coverage required by said lender.

Upon reflection of this situation, I realized that a dishonest agent could easily steer clients into this kind of situation on purpose. Not sure whether she is on commission, but that would be sufficient motive.

Between Hanlon and Occam’s razors, I want to believe it was an honest mistake, but I wanted to hear the opinions and stories from this crowd. Is this kind of experience (un)common?

Ask HN: Is It Age, or Am I Losing Interest in Programming?
text:
I'm working remotely for a US-based company, and lately, I've been unproductive. I am not slacking off it's just the number of tasks I am being given is not that high. I am finishing off my tasks and spending my whole day either on Reddit or Slacking off around the house. When I was at college I used to find interesting projects and work on them, I seem to like to write code.

I got recommended to work on a side project that's far away from my work, however, I didn't have the motivation/discipline/interest in that as well.

I ruled out depression by visiting my doctor.

Is anyone else passing through similar times? Is it okay? Should I be worried?

Ask HN: Habits that have improved your life in many dimensions
text:
Career, love-life, education, health, wealth, finance, family, marriage, etc all are different dimensions of one's life. And habits are the building block of one's life.

What habits have you built for yourself (maybe by rectifying past detrimental habits or building entirely new ones) that have improved your life in many dimensions? If possible describe a bit about what role the habits played in improving your life.

Show HN: Shared Repository of Links for Teams
text:
Hi all at HN, over the past few months, I have been working building a self-managed shared repository of links for teams - Stacks. It is an automated bookmarking service and a noise-less collaboration platform for teams. It provides an easy and pleasant search of your saved content and favorites. Let me know how it works for you. If you currently use another productivity tool or system - let me know in the comments.

Use case of stacks Stacks can be used for a variety of purposes, some of the most common use cases include: 1. Bookmark management: Stacks allows users to save and organize all their favorite websites and links in one place, making it easy to find what they need later.

2. Team collaboration: Stacks allows teams to share links, documents, and other resources in one shared space, making it easy for everyone to access and collaborate on important information.

3. Research and content curation: Stacks can be used to save and organize research materials, articles, and other resources for a specific topic or project.

4. Customer Knowledge base: Professionals such as Financial Advisors can curate and create shared knowledge-base for their customers such as best mutual funds, stocks, insurance. Personal trainers can create repository of best workouts. Influencers can curate best products. As a shared repository with google extension, when installed, can provide customers more accurate and trusted information.

5. Personal organization: Stacks can be used to save and organize personal information such as shopping lists, to-do lists, and personal documents.

6. Online Learning: Stacks can be used to save and organize all your online learning materials, such as course materials, video tutorials, and certification links.

7. Information archiving: Stacks can be used to archive and save old information, making it easy to find and access later.

8. Social Media management: Stacks can be used to save and organize all your social media accounts, influencers and information in one place.

9. Digital Scrapbooking: Stacks can be used to save and organize all the digital memories
